Soon after the 1909 Opium Exclusion Act, the Harrison Act of 1914 expanded the former through the regulation of all, “opium and coca and their derivatives.”20 While it did not call for a complete ban on all forms of these habit-forming substances, the stringent restrictions of the Harrison Act were the most severe antinarcotic legislation put forth to date.21 The Harrison Act primarily reflected the growing concern over the adverse effects of cocaine, as its use and abuse had become widespread by 1914. Purified cocaine became commercially available in 1884 and according to William A. Hammond, one of America’s most prominent neurologists of the time: “cocaine was no more habit-forming than coffee or tea.”22 For several decades after purified
