Equipped and empowered, municipal police departments hit the streets, especially the streets deemed “high-crime.” This being said, these police departments overwhelmingly targeted their surveillance and law enforcement efforts toward urban black neighborhoods. As Elizabeth Hinton explains, “by treating urban crime as a specific phenomenon that could be predicted and contained,” the militarized police “rationalized the concentrated deployment of police officers in black communities.”43 With the constant presence of a combative police, already vulnerable black youth were rendered defenseless against the overzealous occupiers of their neighborhoods. The police became the physical representations of the ‘law and order’ movement as they came to represent enforcement of order rather than servants of the communities they served.
